{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
'''Quota Elimination''' is an initiative to eliminate the use of [[Import quota|quotas]] in all [[textile]] and [[clothing]] trade between nations which are members of the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO). Doing so was one of the key commitments undertaken at the  WTO [[Uruguay Round]] in 1994 to retire the [[Multi Fibre Arrangement]]. The ATC, that is the WTO [[Multi Fibre Arrangement|Agreement on Textile and Clothing]], is the regulation governing textile and clothing and implements this commitment. 

The agreement established a ten-year period which would eliminate the use of quotas in all textile and clothing trade between WTO nations.  It expired on December 31, 2004. As of January 1, 2005, the garment and fabric trade worldwide is operating without quotas.  To ensure the respect of [[Bilateralism|bilateral]] textile agreements, goods shipped prior to January 1, 2005 and subject to the 2004 quotas will be subject to the import regime of 2004 even if they are presented to [[customs]] before January 1.  

To avoid excessive burdens on trade and customs, as of April 1, 2005, all garments and fabrics will trade freely into the [[European Union]] (EU). Although the quotas have been eliminated, the regulation also sets up a [[Statistics|statistical]] monitoring system for the imports of textiles and clothing into the EU. This system is to provide information regarding the chance of [[Disruptive technology|market disruptions]] and will allow for the governing body to closely follow the trade in this new environment. This regulation is beneficial for [[Canada|Canadian]] clothing and fabric manufacturers because now there are fewer restrictions. It is hoped by some{{Who|date=April 2017}} that this ruling will open up the [[Europe]]an market in the near future.{{When|date=April 2017}} Benefits of the abolition of quotas are also expected to textile companies in India and Pakistan.

